Quality Control: Hashed cells

Ramon Massoni-Badosa

4/20/2020

1 Introduction

According to Luecken MD et al., “if the distribution of QC covariates differ between samples, QC thresholds should be determined separately for each sample”. As hashed and non-hashed samples have different library size distributions, the thresholds that separate good- from poor-quality cells will therefore be different. In this notebook, we will filter out low-quality cells and genes for hashed samples.

3 Singlets vs Negatives

To start with, let us compare the QC metrics distribution between “Negative” and “Singlets”. We want to verify that Negative cells are indeed empty droplets:

# Calculate percentage of mitochondrial expression
tonsil_hashed$pct_mt <- PercentageFeatureSet(
  tonsil_hashed,
  pattern = "^MT-"
)


# Plot
vars <- c("nCount_RNA", "nFeature_RNA", "pct_mt")
y_labs <- c(
  "Library Size (total UMI)",
  "Number of Detected Genes",
  "% mitochondrial expression"
)
neg_vs_singl_ggs <- purrr::map2(vars, y_labs, function(x, y_lab) {
  tonsil_hashed@meta.data %>%
    dplyr::filter(HTO_classification.global != "Doublet") %>%
    dplyr::mutate(HTO_classification.global = factor(
      HTO_classification.global,
      levels = c("Singlet", "Negative")
    )) %>% 
    ggplot(aes_string(
        "HTO_classification.global",
        x,
        fill = "HTO_classification.global"
      )) +
      geom_boxplot() +
      labs(x = "", y = y_lab) +
      theme_bw() +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 11),
            axis.title.y = element_text(size = 13),
            legend.position = "none")
})
neg_vs_singl_ggs[[1]] +
  scale_y_log10()

neg_vs_singl_ggs[[2]] +
  scale_y_log10()

neg_vs_singl_ggs[[3]]

4 Distribution of QC variables

First, we want to see how the main QC variables distribute across samples. This will help us interpret the results downstream, as we will know which are the samples with lower quality.

4.1 Signal-to-noise ratio (cell hashing)

# Calculate mean SNR
snr_means_df <- tonsil_hashed@meta.data %>%
  dplyr::group_by(library_name) %>%
  dplyr::summarise(
    mean_snr = round(mean(hashing_snr), 2),
    sd_snr = round(sd(hashing_snr), 2)
  ) %>%
  dplyr::arrange(desc(mean_snr))
DT::datatable(snr_means_df)

5 Filter out cells

We aim to detect and exclude empty droplets or lysed cells. Lysed cells have 3 hallmarks: (1) low library size (total UMI), (2) low library complexity (number of detected genes) and (3) high fraction of mitochondrial expression (cytosolic mRNA leaks out of the cell). Let us start by visualizing their univariate distributions.

5.1 Library Size

lib_size_hist <- tonsil_hashed@meta.data %>%
  plot_histogram_qc(x = "nCount_RNA", x_lab = "Library Size (log10(total UMI))") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = min_lib_size, linetype = "dashed", color = "red")
lib_size_hist1 <- lib_size_hist +
    scale_x_log10() +
    geom_vline(xintercept = max_lib_size, linetype = "dashed", color = "red")
lib_size_hist2 <- lib_size_hist +
    scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 4000)) +
    xlab("Library Size (total UMI)") +

lib_size_hist1 + lib_size_hist2

5.6 Subset empty droplets and lysed cells

metadata_before_qc <- tonsil_hashed@meta.data
is_low_quality <- 
  tonsil_hashed$nCount_RNA < min_lib_size |
  tonsil_hashed$nFeature_RNA < min_n_genes |
  tonsil_hashed$pct_mt > max_pct_mt
table(is_low_quality)
## is_low_quality
##  FALSE   TRUE 
## 297190  30913
tonsil_hashed$keep_cells <- !is_low_quality
Idents(tonsil_hashed) <- "keep_cells"
tonsil_hashed <- subset(tonsil_hashed, idents = TRUE)
metadata_after_qc <- tonsil_hashed@meta.data

5.7 Annotate potential doublets

To aid in the detection and exclusion of doublets, we will identify those outlier cell barcodes that have an abnormally high number of detected genes or library size. Downstream, we will leverage this annotation together with the ones from scrublet and cell hashing to discard clusters composed of a high number of doublets.

tonsil_hashed$has_high_lib_size <- 
  tonsil_hashed$nCount_RNA > max_lib_size |
  tonsil_hashed$nFeature_RNA > max_n_genes
table(tonsil_hashed$has_high_lib_size)

##  FALSE   TRUE 
## 294956   2234

5.8 QC summary table

qc_before <- metadata_before_qc %>%
  group_by(gem_id) %>% 
  summarise(num_cells_before_qc = n())
qc_after <- metadata_after_qc %>%
  group_by(gem_id) %>%
  summarise(
    num_cells_after_qc = n(),
    average_library_size = mean(nCount_RNA),
    average_num_detected_genes = mean(nFeature_RNA),
    average_mitochondrial_fraction = mean(pct_mt)
  )
qc_table <- left_join(qc_before, qc_after, by = "gem_id")
DT::datatable(qc_table)

6 Filter out genes

According to Luecken MD et al.: “A guideline to setting this threshold is to use the minimum cell cluster size that is of interest and leaving some leeway for dropout effects. For example, filtering out genes expressed in fewer than 20 cells may make it difficult to detect cell clusters with fewer than 20 cells. For datasets with high dropout rates, this threshold may also complicate the detection of larger clusters. The choice of threshold should scale with the number of cells in the dataset and the intended downstream analysis.”

Since we want to detect rare cell types in the tonsil, we will be very permissive and retain genes that are expressed in at least 5 cells.

6.1 Set threshold

n_cells <- Matrix::rowSums(tonsil_hashed[["RNA"]]@counts > 0)
gene_qc <- n_cells %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(n_cells)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 100, alpha = 0.75) +
    scale_x_log10("Number of cells") +
    theme_bw() 
gene_qc +
  geom_vline(xintercept = min_cells, linetype = "dashed", color = "red")

6.2 Plot genes with highest expression

top_50_genes <- sort(n_cells, decreasing = TRUE)[1:50]
top_50_genes_df <- data.frame(
  gene = names(top_50_genes),
  n_cells = top_50_genes
)
top_50_genes_df %>%
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(gene, n_cells), n_cells)) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(x = "", y = "Number of expressing cells") +
    coord_flip()
